<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1916-10-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1916-10-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="105" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d105">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.00/2544</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Peck</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 115</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Tsingtau</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1916-10-06">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 6, 1916</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my despatch No. 113, of
                            September 26, 1916, regarding political conditions along the Shantung
                            Railway, I have the honor to state that the rebel organization at Kaomi,
                            66 miles from <pb facs="0172" n="96" xml:id="pg_96"/> Tsingtau on the
                            railway, submitted to the Central Government some days ago, and is now
                            engaged in disbanding troops. This office has been unable to learn the
                            details of the capitulation, but the region is quiet.</p>
                        <p>A copy of this despatch has been sent to the American Legation at Peking
                            and to the American Consulate at Chefoo.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Willys R. Peck</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>